<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>147</anchor>  <taxon>Theorem</taxon> <addr>axt-0007</addr>  <route>axt-0007.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>8</month> <day>19</day></date>  <title>Unary formal topologies and Scott domains</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A formal topology <tex>\mathcal{A}</tex> is <link href="axt-0006.xml" type="local" title="Scott Formal Topology">Scott</link> iff <tex>\mathsf{Pt} ( \mathcal{A} )</tex> is a Scott domain.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>148</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-0006</addr>  <route>axt-0006.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>8</month> <day>19</day></date> <authors><author>Ayberk Tosun</author> </authors> <title>Scott Formal Topology</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Let <tex>\mathcal{A}  = (S,  \cdot , 1,  \lhd ,  \mathsf{Pos} )</tex> be a formal topology.
  <tex>\mathcal{A}</tex> is called <em>Scott</em> if its cover is unary i.e. it satisfies
  <tex display="block">    a  \lhd  U  \iff   \mathsf{Pos} (a)  \rightarrow   \exists  b  \in  U, \  a  \lhd   \{  b  \} .
  </tex></p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>